<LIST>
<ITEM>CHAP. I. We depart for Europe&mdash;a mi&s;under&s;tand|ing ari&s;es between the captain and &s;urgeon through the &s;candalous a&s;per&s;ions of Crampley&mdash;the captain dies&mdash;Crampley tyranni&s;es over the &s;urgeon, who falls a victim to his cruelty&mdash;I am al&s;o ill u&s;ed&mdash;the &s;hip &s;trikes&mdash;the behaviour of Crampley and the &s;eamen on that occa&s;ion&mdash;I get on &s;hore, challenge the captain to &s;in|gle combat&mdash;am treacherou&s;ly knocked down, wound|ed, and robbed, 1</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. II. I get up and crawl into a barn, where I am in danger of peri&s;hing through the fear of the country people&mdash;their inhumanity&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> am &s;uccoured by a re|puted witch&mdash;her &s;tory&mdash;her advice&mdash;&s;he recommends me as a valet to a &s;ingle lady, who&s;e character &s;he explains, 5</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. III. My reception by that lady&mdash;I become ena|moured of Narci&s;&s;a&mdash;recount the particulars of my la&s;t misfortune&mdash;acquire the good opinion of my mi&s;tre&s;s&mdash;an account of the young &s;quire&mdash;I am made ac|quainted with more paticulars of Narci&s;&s;a's &s;ituation&mdash;conceive a mortal hatred again&s;t Sir Timothy&mdash;I examine my lady's library and performances&mdash;her ex|travagant behaviour, 13</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. IV. She is &s;urpri&s;ed at my learning&mdash;communi|cates her performances to me&mdash;I impart &s;ome of mine to her&mdash;am mortified at her &s;aint prai&s;e&mdash;Narci&s;&s;a ap|proves of my production&mdash;I gain an involuntary con|que&s;t over the cook-wench and dairy-maid&mdash;their mu|tual re&s;entment and in&s;inuations&mdash;the jealou&s;y of their lovers, 19</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. V. Narci&s;&s;a, being in danger from the brutality of Sir Timothy, is re&s;cued by me, who revenge my&s;elf on my rival&mdash;I declare my pa&s;&s;ion, and retreat to the &s;ea &s;ide&mdash;I am &s;urrounded by &s;mugglers, and carried to Boulogne&mdash;I find my uncle Lieutenant Bowling in great di&s;tre&s;s, and relieve him&mdash;our conver&s;ation, 25</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. VI. He takes his pa&s;&s;age in a cutter for Deal&mdash;we are acco&s;ted by a prie&s;t, who proves to be a Scotchman&mdash;his profe&s;&s;ions of friend&s;hip&mdash;he is affronted by the
<PB REF="027715_0497_0FD5EF846E518F28">
lieutenant, who afterwards appea&s;es him by &s;ubmi&s;&s;ion&mdash;my uncle embarks&mdash;I am introduced by the prie&s;t to a capuchin, in who&s;e company I &s;et out for Paris&mdash;the character of my fellow-traveller&mdash;an adventure on the road&mdash;I am &s;hocked at his behaviour, 33</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. VII. We lodge at a hou&s;e near Amiens, where I am robbed by the capuchin, who e&s;capes while I am a&s;leep&mdash;I go to Noyons in &s;earch of him, but without &s;ucce&s;s&mdash;I make my condition known to &s;everal peo|ple, but find no relief&mdash;I grow de&s;perate&mdash;join a com|pany of &s;oldiers&mdash;inli&s;t in the regiment of Picardy&mdash;we are ordered into Germany&mdash;I find the fatigues of the march almo&s;t intolerable&mdash;quarrel with my com|rade in a di&s;pute upon politics&mdash;he challenges me to the field, wounds and di&s;arms me, 40</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. VIII. The Ga&s;con does not u&s;e his victory with all the moderation that might have been expected&mdash;in order to be revenged, I learn the &s;cience of defence&mdash;We join Mare&s;chal Duc de Noailles&mdash;are engaged with the allies at Dettingen, and put to flight&mdash;the be|haviour of the French &s;oldiers on that occa&s;ion&mdash;I in|du&s;triou&s;ly &s;eek another combat with the old Ga&s;con, and vanqui&s;h him in my turn&mdash;our regiment is put in|to winter-quarters at Rheims, where I find my friend Strap&mdash;our recognition&mdash;he &s;upplies me with money, and procures my di&s;charge&mdash;we take a trip to Paris, from whence we &s;et out for London, by the way of Flanders, where we &s;afely arrive, 46</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. IX. I inquire about my uncle, and under&s;tand he is gone to &s;ea&mdash;take lodgings at Charing-cro&s;s&mdash;go to the play, where I meet with an adventure&mdash;I go to an ordinary; the gue&s;ts de&s;cribed&mdash;become acquainted with Medlar and Doctor Wagtail, 56</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. X. Wagtail introduces me to a &s;et of fine gentle|men, with whom I &s;pend the evening at the tavern&mdash;our conver&s;ation&mdash;the characters of my new compani|ons&mdash;the doctor is roa&s;ted&mdash;the i&s;&s;ue of our debauch, 70</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XI. Strap communicates to me a conque&s;t he had made on a chandler's widow&mdash;finds him&s;elf mi&s;erably mi&s;taken&mdash;I go to an opera&mdash;admire Melinda&mdash;am cautioned by Banter&mdash;go to the a&s;&s;embly at Hamp&s;tead&mdash;dance with that young lady&mdash;receive an in&s;olent
<PB REF="027715_0498_0FD5EF861137D258">
me&s;&s;age from Bragwell, who&s;e mettle is &s;oon cooled&mdash;am in favour with my mi&s;tre&s;s, whom I vi&s;it next day, and am bubbled out of eighteen guineas at cards&mdash;Strap triumphs at my &s;ucce&s;s, but is a&s;toni&s;hed at my expence&mdash;Banter comes to my lodging, is very &s;ar|ca&s;tical at my expence, and borrows five guineas from me as a proof of his friend&s;hip, 80</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XII. We repair to the coffee-hou&s;e, where we overhear a curious di&s;pute between Wagtail and Medlar, which is referred to our deci&s;ion&mdash;the doctor gives us an account of his experiment&mdash;Medlar is roa&s;ted by Banter at the ordinary&mdash;the old gentle|man's advice to me, 89</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XIII. I receive a challenge&mdash;the con&s;equences of it&mdash;the quarrel being made up, I am put in arre&s;t by the care and affection of Strap, but immediately re|lea&s;ed upon explaining my affair&mdash;the behaviour of Mr. O'Regan and his two friends&mdash;I vi&s;it Melinda, whom I divert with an account of the duel&mdash;I propo&s;e marriage&mdash;&s;he refers the matter to her mother, of whom I make a &s;olemn demand of her daughter&mdash;the old lady's behaviour&mdash;I am di&s;carded, re&s;ent their di&s;dain, 93</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XIV. I long to be revenged on Melinda&mdash;apply to Banter for his a&s;&s;i&s;tance&mdash;he contrives a &s;cheme for that purpo&s;e, which is put in execution with great &s;ucce&s;s&mdash;I make an attempt on the heart of Mi&s;s Gripewell, but am di&s;appointed&mdash;grow melancholy at my di&s;appointment, and have recour&s;e to the bot|tle&mdash;receive a billet-doux&mdash;am ravi&s;hed with the con|tents&mdash;find my&s;elf involved in an intrigue, which I imagined would make my fortune&mdash;am confounded at my mi&s;take, which bani&s;hes all thoughts of matrimony 100</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XV. I cultivate an acquaintance with two noble|men&mdash;am introduced to Earl Strutwell&mdash;his kind pro|mi&s;e and invitation&mdash;the behaviour of his porter and lackey&mdash;he receives me with an appearance of uncom|mon affection&mdash;undertakes to &s;peak in my behalf to the mini&s;ter&mdash;informs me of his &s;ucce&s;s, and wi&s;hes me joy&mdash;introduces a conver&s;ation about Petronius Arbiter&mdash;falls in love with my watch, which I pre&s;s upon him&mdash;I make a pre&s;ent of a diamond ring to lord
<PB REF="027715_0499_0FD5EF876CDE86C8">
Straddle&mdash;impart my good fortune to Strap and Ban|ter, who di&s;abu&s;es me, to my utter mortification, 111</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XVI. I attempt to recover my watch and jewel, but to no purpo&s;e&mdash;re&s;olve to revenge my&s;elf on Strutwell by my importunity&mdash;am reduced to my la&s;t guinea&mdash;obliged to inform Strap of my nece&s;&s;ity, who is almo&s;t di&s;tracted with the news&mdash;but neverthele&s;s obliged to pawn my be&s;t &s;word for pre&s;ent &s;ub&s;i&s;tence&mdash;that &s;mall &s;upply being exhau&s;ted, I am almo&s;t &s;tu|pified with my misfortunes&mdash;go to the gaming table by the advice of Banter, and come off with unexpected &s;ucce&s;s&mdash;Strap's exta&s;y&mdash;Mrs. Gawky waits upon me, profe&s;&s;es remor&s;e for her perfidy, and implores my a&s;&s;i&s;tance&mdash;I do my&s;elf a piece of ju&s;tice by her means, and afterwards reconcile her to her father, 119</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XVII. I purcha&s;e new clothes&mdash;reprimand Strut|well and Straddle&mdash;Banter propo&s;es another matri|monial &s;cheme&mdash;I accept of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> terms&mdash;&s;et out for Bath in the &s;tage coach, with the young lady and her mother&mdash;the behaviour of an officer and a lawyer, our fellow-travellers de&s;cribed&mdash;a &s;mart dialogue be|tween my mi&s;tre&s;s and the captain, 127</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XVIII. Day breaking, I have the plea&s;ure of viewing the per&s;on of Mi&s;s Snapper, whom I had not &s;een before&mdash;the &s;oldier is witty upon me&mdash;is offend|ed&mdash;talks much of his valour&mdash;is reprimanded by a grave gentlewoman&mdash;we are alarmed with the cry of highwaymen&mdash;I get out of the coach, and &s;tand on my own defence&mdash;they ride off without having <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">|tacked us&mdash;I pur&s;ue them&mdash;one of them is throw<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> from his hor&s;e, and taken&mdash;I return to the coach&mdash;am complimented by Mi&s;s Snapper&mdash;the captain's be|haviour on the occa&s;ion&mdash;the prude reproaches me in a &s;oliloquy&mdash;I upbraid her in the &s;ame manner&mdash;the behaviour of Mrs. Snapper at breakfa&s;t di&s;obliges me&mdash;the lawyer is witty on the officer, who threatens him, 133</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XIX. I re&s;olve to ingratiate my&s;elf with the mo|ther, and am favoured by accident&mdash;the preci&s;e lady finds her hu&s;band, and quits the coach&mdash;the captain is di&s;appointed of his dinner&mdash;we arrive at Bath&mdash;I accompany Mi&s;s Snapper to the Long-room, where
<PB REF="027715_0500_0FD5EF890D288F90">
&s;he is attacked by Beau N&mdash;&s;h, and turns the laugh again&s;t him&mdash;I make love to her, and receive a check&mdash;&s;quire her to an a&s;&s;embly, where I am ble&s;t with a &s;ight of my dear Narci&s;&s;a, which di&s;compo&s;es me &s;o much, that Mi&s;s Snapper, ob&s;erving my di&s;order, is at &s;ome pains to di&s;cover the cau&s;e&mdash;is piqued at the occa&s;ion, and in our way home pays me a &s;arca&s;tic compliment&mdash;I am met by Mi&s;s Williams, who is maid and confidante of Narci&s;&s;a&mdash;&s;he acquaints me with her lady's regard for me while under the di&s;|gui&s;e of a &s;ervant, and de&s;cribes the tran&s;ports of Narci&s;&s;a on &s;eeing me at the a&s;&s;embly in the character of a gentleman&mdash;I am &s;urpri&s;ed with an account of her aunt's marriage, and make an appointment to meet Mi&s;s Williams next day, 140</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XX. I become acquainted with Narci&s;&s;a's bro|ther, who invites me to his hou&s;e, where I am intro|duced to that adorable creature&mdash;after dinner the &s;quire retires to take his nap&mdash;Freeman, gue&s;&s;ing the &s;ituation of my thoughts, withdraws likewi&s;e on pre|tence of bu&s;ine&s;s&mdash;I declare my pa&s;&s;ion for Narci&s;&s;a&mdash;am well received&mdash;charmed with her conver&s;ation&mdash;the &s;quire detains us to &s;upper&mdash;I elude his de&s;ign by &s;tratagem, and get home &s;ober, 149</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XXI. Mi&s;s Williams informs me of Narci&s;&s;a's approbation of my flame&mdash;I appea&s;e the &s;quire&mdash;write to my mi&s;tre&s;s&mdash;am ble&s;&s;ed with an an&s;wer&mdash;beg leave of her brother to dance with her at a ball; obtain his con&s;ent and her's&mdash;enjoy a private conver&s;ation with her&mdash;am perplexed with reflections&mdash;have the honour of appearing her partner at the ball&mdash;we are compli|mented by a certain nobleman&mdash;he di&s;covers &s;ome &s;ymp|toms of pa&s;&s;ion for Narci&s;&s;a&mdash;I am &s;tung with jealou&s;y&mdash;Narci&s;&s;a, alarmed, retires&mdash;I ob&s;erve Melinda in the company&mdash;the &s;quire is captivated by her beauty, 158</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XXII. Tortured with jealou&s;y, I go home and abu&s;e Strap&mdash;receive a me&s;&s;age from Narci&s;&s;a, in con|&s;equence of which I ha&s;ten to her apartment, where her endearing a&s;&s;urances bani&s;h all my doubts and appre|hen&s;ions&mdash;in my retreat di&s;cover &s;omebody in the dark, whom, &s;u&s;pecting to be a &s;py, I re&s;olve to kill; but, to my great &s;urpri&s;e, am convinced of his being
<PB REF="027715_0501_0FD5EF8DE9E97248">
no other than Strap&mdash;Melinda &s;landers me&mdash;I become acquainted with Lord Quiverwit, who endeavours to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ound me with regard to Narci&s;&s;a&mdash;the &s;quire is intro|duced to his lord&s;hip, and grows cold towards me&mdash;I learn from my confidante, that this nobleman profe&s;&s;es honourable love to my mi&s;tre&s;s, who continues faithful to me, notwith&s;tanding the &s;candalous reports &s;he had heard to my prejudice&mdash;I am mortified with an a&s;&s;u|rance that her whole fortune depends on the plea&s;ure of her brother&mdash;Mr. Freeman condoles me on the de|cline of my character, which I vindicate &s;o much to his &s;atisfaction, that he undertakes to combat fame in my behalf, 166</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XXIII. I receive an extraordinary me&s;&s;age at the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of the Long-room, which I however enter, and affront the &s;quire, who threatens to take the law of me&mdash;rebuke Melinda for her malice&mdash;&s;he weeps with vexation&mdash;Lord Quiverwit is &s;evere upon me&mdash;I re|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ort his &s;arca&s;m&mdash;am received with the utmo&s;t tender|ne&s;s by Narci&s;&s;a, who de&s;ires to hear the &s;tory of my life&mdash;we vow eternal con&s;tancy to one another&mdash;I re|tire&mdash;am waked by a me&s;&s;enger who brings a chal|lenge from Quiverwit, whom I meet, engage, and vanqui&s;h, 171</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XXIV. I am vi&s;ited by Freeman, with whom I ap|pear in public, and am care&s;&s;ed&mdash;am &s;ent for by Lord Quiverwit, who&s;e pre&s;ence I quit in a pa&s;&s;ion&mdash;Nar|ci&s;&s;a is carried off by her brother&mdash;I intend to pur&s;ue him, and am di&s;&s;uaded by my friend&mdash;engage in play, and lo&s;e all my money&mdash;&s;et out for London&mdash;try my fortune at the gaming-table without &s;ucce&s;s&mdash;receive a letter from Narci&s;&s;a&mdash;bilk my tailor, 177</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XXV. I am arre&s;ted&mdash;carried to the Mar&s;hal&s;ea&mdash;find my old acquaintance beau Jack&s;on in that jail&mdash;he informs me of his adventures&mdash;Strap arrives, and with difficulty is comforted&mdash;Jack&s;on introduces me to a poet&mdash;I admire his conver&s;ation and capacity&mdash;am deeply affected with my misfortune&mdash;Strap hires him|&s;elf as a Journeyman barber, 18<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"></ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap XXVI. I read Melopoyn's tragedy, and conceive a va&s;t opinion of his genius&mdash;he recounts his adven|tures, 190</ITEM>
<ITEM><PB REF="027715_0502_0FD5EF9020F77400">
Chap. XXVII. The continuation and conclu&s;ion of Mr. Melopoyn's &s;tory, 198</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XXVIII. I am &s;eized with a deep melancholy, and become a &s;loven&mdash;am relieved by my uncle&mdash;he prevails upon me to engage with his owners, as a &s;ur|geon of the &s;hip which he commands&mdash;he makes me a con&s;iderable pre&s;ent&mdash;entertains Strap as his &s;teward&mdash;I take leave of my friends, and go on board&mdash;the &s;hip arrives at the Downs, 210</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XXIX. I &s;et out for Su&s;&s;ex&mdash;con&s;ult Mrs. Sagely&mdash;achieve an interview with Narci&s;&s;a&mdash;return to the &s;hip&mdash;we get clear of the channel&mdash;I learn our de&s;ti|nation&mdash;we are cha&s;ed by a large &s;hip&mdash;the company are di&s;mayed, and encouraged by the captain's &s;peech&mdash;our pur&s;ue<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> happens to be an Engli&s;h man of war&mdash;we arrive on the coa&s;t of Guinea, purcha&s;e 400 negroes, &s;ail for Paraguay, get &s;afe into the river of Plate, and &s;ell our cargo to great advantage, 217</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XXX. I am invited to the villa of a Spani&s;h don, where we meet with an Engli&s;h gentleman, and make a very intere&s;ting di&s;covery&mdash;we leave Buenos Ayres, and arrive at Jamaica, 226</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XXXI. I vi&s;it my old friend Thomp&s;on&mdash;we &s;et &s;ail for Europe&mdash;meet with an odd adventure&mdash;ar|rive in England&mdash;I ride acro&s;s the country from Port&s;mouth to Su&s;&s;ex&mdash;conver&s;e with Mrs. Sagely, who informs me of Narci&s;&s;a's being in London&mdash;in con|&s;equence of this intelligence I proceed to Canterbury&mdash;meet with my old friend Morgan&mdash;arrive at Lon|don&mdash;vi&s;it Narci&s;&s;a&mdash;introduce my father to her&mdash;he is charmed with her good &s;en&s;e and beauty&mdash;we come to a determination of demanding her brother's con|&s;ent to our marriage, 234</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XXXII. My father makes a pre&s;ent to Narci&s;&s;a&mdash;the letter is di&s;patched to her brother&mdash;I appear among my acquaintance&mdash;Banter's behaviour&mdash;the &s;quire refu&s;es his con&s;ent&mdash;my uncle comes to town&mdash;approves of my choice&mdash;I am married&mdash;we meet the &s;quire and his lady at the play&mdash;our acquaintance is courted, 244</ITEM>
<ITEM>Chap. XXXIII. My father intends to vi&s;it the place of his nativity&mdash;we propo&s;e to accompany him&mdash;my un|cle
<PB REF="027715_0503_0FD5EF91F2F49610">
renews his will in my favour, determining to go to &s;ea again&mdash;we &s;et out for Scotland&mdash;arrive at Edinburgh&mdash;purcha&s;e our paternal e&s;tate&mdash;proceed to it&mdash;halt at the town where I was educated&mdash;take up my bond to Crab&mdash;the behaviour of Potion and his wife, and one of my female cou&s;ins&mdash;our reception at the e&s;tate&mdash;Strap marries Mi&s;s Williams, and is &s;ettled by my father to his own &s;atisfaction&mdash;I am more and more happy, 250</ITEM>
</LIST>
